{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65efa051-896f-42fd-95d2-6199f35fe5f9","content":"Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` file in your workspace root with this configuration:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — launches your server via `dotnet run`. Adjust the `--project` path if needed (it's relative to the workspace root).\n- You can add `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` if your server needs environment variables.\n\nOnce saved, open the Copilot chat in agent mode — it will automatically discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"622ab410-67d2-4912-8119-a0a555eae26e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're just asking how to configure mcp.json. I can provide guidance on this.\n\nFor VS Code agent mode, you configure MCP servers in `.vscode/mcp.json` (workspace-level) or in user settings. The format for a stdio-based C# MCP server using `dotnet run` would be something like:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nClosing out the JSON structure...","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"F3D2:2BFBA0:10E64E:151F35:69F54DE7"},"id":"31de10ca-320c-427c-baae-60ee50629486","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:05:59.013Z","parentId":"1f3aafc0-96ce-4c07-aee2-a6d950849532"}
